05611nam a22009015i 9780520971691DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018048200  a97805209716917 a10.1525/97805209716912doi  a(DE-B1597)534779  a(OCoLC)1075545919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aRC451.S62bK55 2019 4aRC451.S62bK55 2019 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a362.2/1096632231 aKilroy-Marac, Katie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Impossible Inheritance :bPostcolonial Psychiatry and the Work of Memory in a West African Clinic /cKatie Kilroy-Marac. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Entanglements -- tRupture: Chasing a Ghost -- t1. Archiving Madness: From Colonial Psychiatry to the Establishment of Fann -- tInterlude: Many Battles -- t2. Origin Stories: Collomb's Fann and Senghor's Senegal -- tRupture: A Letter Unanswered -- t3. Nostalgic for Modernity (Or, Looking Back on a Golden Age) -- tInterlude: A Terrible Cry fr om the Past -- t4. The Ink That Marked History -- tInterlude: Each in His Corner -- t5. Strategic Ambivalence -- tRupture: A Thing I Could Not See (The Joola) -- t6. Distinctions of the Present -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWeaving sound historical research with rich ethnographic insight, An Impossible Inheritance tells the story of the emergence, disavowal, and afterlife of a distinctive project in transcultural psychiatry initiated at the Fann Psychiatric Clinic in Dakar, Senegal during the 1960s and 1970s. Today's clinic remains haunted by its past and Katie Kilroy-Marac brilliantly examines the complex forms of memory work undertaken by its affiliates over a sixty year period. Through stories such as that of the the ghost said to roam the clinic's halls, the mysterious death of a young doctor sometimes attributed to witchcraft, and the spirit possession ceremonies that may have taken place in Fann's courtyard, Kilroy-Marac argues that memory work is always an act of the imagination and a moral practice with unexpected temporal, affective, and political dimensions. By exploring how accounts about the Fann Psychiatric Clinic and its past speak to larger narratives of postcolonial and neoliberal transformation, An Impossible Inheritance examines the complex relationship between memory, history, and power within the institution and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aPsychiatric clinicszSenegalzDakar. 0aPsychiatryzSenegalzDakarxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1970s.  adakar.  afann psychiatric clinic.  aghosts.  ahaunted by the past.  ahaunted.  ahistory.  aimagination.  amemory work.  amoral practice.  amysterious death.  aneoliberal transformation.  apolitical dimensions.  apost colonial transformation.  asenegal.  aspirit possession ceremonies.  atranscultural psychiatry.  aunexpected temporal dimensions.  awitchcraft.  ayoung doctor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Co